I"Xõ<p>Twitter is a great resource for engaging with the academic community. For example, I saw this Tweet by <a href="https://twitter.com/PhD_Genie" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">PhD Genie</a> asking users to name one positive skill learned during their PhD. I love this question for a number of reasons. First, it helps PhDs reframe their experience so it‚Äôs applicable outside of academia - which can help when applying to jobs. Second, it‚Äôs really cool to see what skills other people have learned during their program.<br />
<!--more--></p>

<figure>
    
    <a href="/assets/notes-images/nps/nps-1.jpg" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
        <img src="/assets/notes-images/nps/nps-1.jpg" alt="Image: PhD Genie Tweet" class="img-fluid mx-auto d-block" />
    </a>
    
    <figcaption><span>PhD Genie Tweet</span></figcaption>
</figure>

<p>I responded to the tweet because during my PhD I learned how to create maps in R. I started by recreating a map from the <a href="https://www.usnewsdeserts.com/&quot;" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">University of North Carolina‚Äôs Hussman School of Journalism‚Äôs News Deserts</a> project (below). Now, I am working on a personal project mapping the U.S. National and State parks.</p>

<figure>
    
    <a href="/assets/notes-images/nps/nps-2.png" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">
        <img src="/assets/notes-images/nps/nps-2.png" alt="Image: Map of US newspapers by county" class="img-fluid mx-auto d-block" />
